The area of a square is \( L=s^{2} \).
Next, let's derive its area function.
\[
\begin{array}{c}
L=s^{2} \\
\frac{d L}{d t}=2 s \frac{d s}{d t}
\end{array}
\]

At \( L=25 \), we can determine the value of \( s \).
\[
\begin{array}{c}
L=s^{2} \\
25=s^{2} \\
s=5
\end{array}
\]

Next, let's determine the rate of change of the area.
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\frac{d L}{d t}=2 s \frac{d s}{d t} \\
\frac{d L}{d t}=2(5) \cdot 6=60 \mathrm{~cm}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{array}
\]

Answer: \( \frac{d L}{d t}=60 \mathrm{~cm}^{2} / \mathrm{s} \)

